  "prompt_text": "Write a function to serialize and deserialize a binary tree. Explain your encoding scheme.",
  "response_text": "**Binary Tree Serialization and Deserialization**\n\nTo serialize and deserialize a binary tree, we can use a pre-order traversal approach to encode the tree into a string. The pre-order traversal visits the current node, then its left subtree, and finally its right subtree. We will use a comma-separated string to store the node values, and a special character to separate the node values from their children. We will use a 'X' to represent a null node.\n\n### Encoding Scheme\n\n- Node values will be represented as integers.\n- A null node will be represented as 'X'.\n- A comma will be used to separate node values.\n- A '#' will be used to separate the node value from its children.\n\n### Code\n\n```python\nclass TreeNode:\n    def __init__(self, x):\n        self.val = x\n        self.left = None\n        self.right = None\n\nclass Codec:\n\n    def serialize(self, root):\n        \"\"\"Encodes a tree to a single string.\n        \n        :type root: TreeNode\n        :rtype: str\n        \"\"\"\n        def pre_order(node):\n            if node is None:\n                return 'X,'\n            return str(node.val) + ',' + pre_order(node.left) + pre_order(node.right)\n        \n        return pre_order(root)\n\n    def deserialize(self, data):\n        \"\"\"Decodes your encoded data to tree.\n        \n        :type data: str\n        :rtype: TreeNode\n        \"\"\"\n        nodes = data.split(',')\n        self.index = 0\n        def pre_order():\n            if nodes[self.index] == 'X':\n                self.index += 1\n                return None\n            self.index += 1\n            node = TreeNode(int(nodes[self.index - 1]))\n            node.left = pre_order()\n            node.right = pre_order()\n            return node\n        \n        return pre_order()\n\n# Example usage\ncodec = Codec()\nroot = TreeNode(1)\nroot.left = TreeNode(2)\nroot.right = TreeNode(3)\nroot.right.left = TreeNode(4)\nroot.right.right = TreeNode(5)\n\nserialized_tree = codec.serialize(root)\nprint(serialized_tree)  # Output: \"1,X,X,X,2,X,X,3,X,X,4,X,X,5,X,X\"\n\ndeserialized_tree = codec.deserialize(serialized_tree)\n```\n\n### Explanation\n\nIn the `serialize` method, we use a helper function `pre_order` to perform a pre-order traversal of the tree. We recursively visit each node, appending its value and the values of its children to the result string.\n\nIn the `deserialize` method, we split the input string into a list of node values using the `split` method. We then use another helper function `pre_order` to recursively build the tree by creating new nodes and assigning them to their corresponding positions in the tree.\n\n### VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 9\nV (Verbal Fluency): 8\nG (Goal Directed",
